<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>A SUMMARY OF THE COMMISSION MTR PROPOSALS AND A COMPARISON WITH RSPCA/EUROGROUP RECOMMENDATIONS</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written submission from the RSPCA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Abstract</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Food security and what it means needs to be taken in the context of the increasing global trade in food and farm products and t</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">he challenges </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">facing the agricultural industry </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">to meet projected global demand.  The default position -  i.e. that this needs to be met with further food production, and by implication, greater intensification of food animal production</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> - needs to be reconsidered.  Achieving a healthier diet, cutting down on food waste and assessing what the UK or Europe can or cannot produce (given increasing global trade and reducing subsidies) all </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">need to be </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">addressed first.   The EU’s progress in securing animal w</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">elfare improvements in  sectors such as pigs, chickens and laying hens</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> in the last seven years must not be undermined</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">.  However</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">,</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> these improvements could be contrary to meeting present forecasted global demand for meat and could put the EU at a disadvantage to products being more intensively </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">produced</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> in other countries.  Further work is required in this area.  </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Climate change is another parameter to be included before any framework can be developed on food security.  Progress on agreeing what s</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">cientific data </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">indicates and getting political agreement on what is required from the British livestock industry </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">to m</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">eet UK greenhouse gas reductions has been </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">patchy.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.84pt; padding-left:5.16pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The RSPCA believes that food needs to be produced in a sustainable and humane manner, and the rush to secure food supplies should not be an excuse to intensify farming at the expense of animal welfare.   Livestock farming should not be considered ‘sustainable’ unless animal welfare is safeguarded. There are a number of factors that need to be considered before any decision is taken that more food – and/or particular classes of food (e.g. livestock products)  - need to be produced.  Firstly, what are the trends in population, changing diets and consumer preference?  Secondly,</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> can the diet</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> be changed to become a healthier and more sustainable one and so concentrate on the production of certain food types.  Thirdly, can new approaches to farming, and challenging of traditional views on what drives efficiency and productivity, highlight the commercial viability and production potential of higher welfare farming systems.  Finally, can we use resources more efficiently, in particular can there be a reduction in food waste.  The default position should not simply be the intensification of food production to produce more food.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.52pt; padding-left:4.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Defining what food security means at a national and European level needs to be taken in the context of global trade agreements, the reform of the EU’s farm subsidy programme and our commitments to meet other international agreements such as reducing climate change emissions.  Some of these wider impact issues have come to fruition in the past year.  There has been an agreement on a reformed Common Agricultural Policy, which should set the scene on agricultural policy for the next decade.  In December 2013, agreement was reached on harmonising customs standards, the first agreement under the World Trade Agreement since it was set up in 1994, which will impact on global agricultural trade.   Negotiations on agreement on climate change reductions also made some progress in November.  However, there has been little high level political progress in the UK on how </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">these changes will </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">impact on</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> overall food security or </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">what </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">sort of </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">food security </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">the UK and EU are looking at</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.89pt; padding-left:5.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The RSPCA believes that the new CAP agreement gives an opportunity for food production to respond to the needs for increased and better (</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> more humanely </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">produced) food production, particularly with the UK government commitment to exercise the maximum modulation of funds from Pillar I to Pillar II.  However, England has not produced any budget lines for improving animal welfare under its Rural </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">evelopment Programme and it is doubtful that this will change in the future. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.59pt; padding-left:4.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">British consumers have consistently stated that they consider animal welfare to be an important issue when choosing food, and that they do not wish to purchase food that is imported from countries using lower standards than in the UK</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">. In the past ten years there have been a number of European legislative agreements to phase out certain close confinement methods of farming, such as Directive 1999/74 which has prohibited the conventional battery cage system for laying hens, the improved standards in chicken farming contained in Directive 2007/43, which via the transposition into national laws, raises the standards for chicken farming in England and Wales to above those in other European countries.  In addition, other laws prohibiting other close confinement systems such as the sow stall and the veal c</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">rate  have now been implemented</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.  The bans on both of these systems</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> in the UK preceded </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">EU-wide phase-outs by 14 and 15 years respectively.   A direction has been agreed at a sector level, that farming needs to be resp</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">onsive to consumer desires for </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">more humane farming systems.  One of the consequences of this may be that this is incompatible with achieving food security at a national or indeed EU level, even on those sectors such as pigs, eggs and beef, where the EU has to date been self sufficient.   It is important for </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">British and European producers </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">using higher welfare standards that they are not penalised financially  by products from systems using lower welfare standards.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.19pt; padding-left:4.81pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">To achieve this, consumers should be given the correct information through labelling.  Central and local government can play a role in ensuring that procurement practices are followed that promote sustainable farming.  Clear, transparent, simple labelling makes it possible for consumers to make an informed choice about the products that they are buying whether on health, welfare or environmental grounds, and provides the opportunity for producers of higher welfare products to gain due recognition  and potentially recover some of their increased production costs (where they exist) in the market place.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.67pt; padding-left:4.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The demand for more humane systems of farming, in response to </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">the public and consumer demand </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">has not affected food security within the EU.  However,</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">although these systems have been prohibited in the EU, there has been a move towards using them in other countries particularly in the developing world such as sub Saharan Africa, India and sout</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">hwest Asia.</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.61pt; padding-left:5.39pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Defining what food security actually is and means at a national or European level needs political direction, which to date has not been </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">much </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">in evidence.  </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">EFRA should recommend that the Government clearly set out what food security means and its impact on policy.  </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">This can then be translated into what this implies in food production which would then determine issues such as the direction of travel required in the Common Agricultural Policy.   Food security is more than just increasing food </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">production or producing it more efficiently it is also about how accessible food is, how much waste there is in food production and consumption and the scope, sale and nature of problems caused by intensifying food production.   Studies have shown how conventional intensive farming is not sustainable nor a long term solution to food security</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Such studies show how conventional, resource intensive farming was fundamentally unsustainable and focussing solely on increased production was not a long term solution to food security.   There have also been examples showing the potential links in some instances between intensifying production and increased disease risks leading to food security issues</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.57pt; padding-left:4.43pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> Some 30-40% of food globally</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">is wasted including waste at each stage of food production</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.  For example, the amount of food thrown away by consumers in some rich countries equals as much food as the entire food production of sub Saharan Africa</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">4</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.  It also includes the high percentage</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">of food particularly in developing countries that never gets to market.  Clearly, addressing the waste issue at a national, regional and global level is important before any further increase in food is demanded. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.67pt; padding-left:4.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Agricultural policy has tended to focus on production and trade rather than improving diet and nutrition.  For the first time in history there are as many overweight people as under nourished people</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">4</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.  The answer must lie in the public sector offering a framework to take into account long term public needs, which can then be adopted by the private sector which has to play the major role in providing solutions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The production of beef and veal shows how UK markets can be reoriented to become more sustainable, improve animal welfare and improve food security.   The Calf Forum, a stakeholder group compromising retailers, NGOs, farmers, producers and processors, was set up in 2006 to increase the domestic markets for veal and beef from male dairy calves instead of exporting them to the continent or killing them soon after birth.  Since it was formed it has demonstrated that welfare linked interests can, with the help of stakeholders drawn from across all relevant sectors, contribute positively to the wellbeing of commercial agriculture – on this occasion by helping to secure greater UK self-sufficiency in beef, as well as the generation of millions of pounds more in calf sales income for dairy farmers, beef farmers, and the national exchequer. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.77pt; padding-left:0.23pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The numbers of calves being exported to the continent has declined by 90% in the past seven years to a projected 7,000 in 2013 as markets have developed in the UK to produce veal and beef from male Holstein calves.   In the same time period, t</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">he number of dairy calves being retained for rearing in the UK has increased by 58% and the number of calves being killed on farm has declined by 36%</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.   UK self sufficiency in beef has increased in the past seven years in part due to the uptake of male dairy calves into the beef and veal markets in the UK. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Food price increases are linked to a variety of factors including weather related bad harvests, commodity market speculation and c</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">hanging patterns of consumption</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">, particularly in the increasingly affluent and  meat-eating middle classes in southern Asia .  Invariably, increasing food prices</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> results</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">a desire to reduce production costs which then risks increasing intensification of farm animals, erroneously perceived by some as being the best/only way to improve efficiency.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.82pt; padding-left:0.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The Calf Forum showed </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">that incentives to rear </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">calves usually centred around the value of calves on the market in the UK – above £50 per calf farm</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">ers decided to rear the calves but</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> below this value calves were either shot at birth or exported to the continent.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">In aiming for UK food security, focus increases on new technologies for food production.  Indeed the UK’s Government focus on increasing food supply through “sustainable intensification” seems to be focused on new technologies delivering these changes.  However, whilst some new technologies can bring benefits to animal welfare (e.g. robotic milking), or are at least ‘welfare neutral’, others can have a negative impact on animal welf</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">are. </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> Discussions on limiting cloning for farm animals highlight the problems of certain new technologies.  Attempts to overturn the EU’s ban on cloning were stopped by</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> the European Parliament in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> and whilst a new Commission proposal is due out in 2013, the same arguments are likely to be repeated, pitching animal welfare concerns on cloning against industry demands to allow cloning because of a perception that it might help to meet increasing food demands  </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Consumers and citizens have clearly expressed their opposition to products from cloned animals and their offspring, resulting in the continuing impasse between the Commission and the Parliament. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Although climate change has already started to affect agricultural production, the switch from intensive livestock systems that was called for in 2008 by the European Parliament has yet to occur.   Climate change is likely to result in changes in agricultural production through changing rainfall patterns and temperature.  More frequent extreme weather events such as drought or flooding and the potential increase in invasive and damaging non-native species and diseases will also affect agricultural production.   The European Union are discussing a new framework on </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">import of alien species which should address the latter point. Ironically</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">, climate change may result in </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">more animals being kept inside to protect their health and welfare. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">However the changes needed from UK agriculture to meet climate chang</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">e-related commitments are less clear.  The 2008 report from the Committee on Climate Change placed agricultural emissions in the UK as fifth most important emission </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">source (after power stations, resident</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">ial, industry, transport).</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">   Its main recommendation for a government developed policy framework still needs to be addressed, as do recommendations  about creating a decline in UK emissions by measures such as use of using new technology or eating less carbon intensive types of meat. These obviously impact on food security.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.54pt; padding-left:0.46pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Clearly, further research is required in the area of assessing the impact of different diets or farming methods on specific greenhouse gas emissions, and also ensuring that any mitigating effects arising from policy decisions should be proofed against effects on animal welfare and the environment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Farmers should not simply be seeking to increase production, they should instead focus on making their systems sustainable. Whilst increased productivity may, in some cases, be achieved without negative impact on welfare (or may even be associated with improved welfare), focusing solely on production levels without being mindful of the consequences can result in welfare problems. Also, increased production does not necessary result in increased profit.  Producing food in a more humane manner is something being demanded by consumers throughout the EU as shown by the two </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">Eurobarmometer</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> surveys on animal welfare.  To support farmers in being more sustainable, we need better, more ‘ joined up’</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> advice and knowledge transfer.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing self sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">UK self-sufficiency in beef is now 85 per cent, compared with 75 per cent in 2007, despite a steep fall in breeding cow numbers. This welcome improvement is due principally to the return of OTM beef to the market, but the increased retention of Holstein bull calves has , as promoted by the Calf Forum</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">5</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">has also positively contributed, though the importance of issues such as price sens</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">itivity should be borne in mind</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">The beef market where f</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">resh beef and burger retailers have developed new markets for purebred dairy bull calves and potential </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">rearers</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt"> and finishers offered objective cost and profit indicators through the Forum’s information dispers</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">al system.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">At the same time the Calf Forum  has helped to focus dairy sector attention on the welfare of the Holstein cow and further encourage improvements in robustness that are already underway through other initiatives.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">December 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 12pt 5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt">Eurobarometer</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt"> No. 229 June 2005 Attitudes of consumers towards the welfare of farmed animal;  </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt">Eurobarometer</span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt"> 270.  March 2007. Attitudes of European citizens towards animal welfare.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt">In 2009, the UN and World Bank-sponsored IAASTD report (International Assessment of Agricultural Knowledge, Science and </span><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt">Technology for Development) was published</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Corbel; font-size:8pt">Bryony A. Jonesa,b,1, Delia </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-